The seminar deals with German language literary texts from the beginning of the twentieth century to our days, introducing to some of the key authors such as Thomas Mann, Rilke, Kafka, Celan, Grass, Dürrenmatt, Böll, Handke and Sebald. The course will concentrate on close reading techniques and hermeneutics and focus on the discussion and analysis of selected literary works. Even though it cannot provide a comprehensive history of literature, it will proceed chronologically to enable the students to better understand the historical basis and development of literary forms and topics.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The course will give the students an overview over the German speaking literature of the 20th and 21st century covering many of the key authors. The crucial developments and topics will be dealt with, covering modernism, post-war literature, the divided and reunified Germany. The students will learn how to analyse different literary texts (prose, poetry and drama).Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After the course, the students will be familiar with a good number of the most important authors and developments in German literary history form the beginning of the 20th century to our times. They will have become accustomed to literary concepts and have acquired skills how to discuss and critically analyse literature of different periods and genres, orally and in writing. They will have developed digital skills such as using search engines and data banks while being aware of their structure and operation modes so that they can critically evaluate the sources and their reliability. Furthermore, they have practised using various word processing functions and creating content in different formats.
